@philip5940 Using old mines for either storage of CO2 is looked into but afaik these are controversially discussed on ground of possible leaks and long term storage as well because this storage can be used as excuse to continue in producing CO2 by combustion or otherwise industrial means.
Then there are also discussion’s on using them as storage for compressed air. My understanding is that unused green energy is used to compress air and use this compressed air when there is not sufficient wind or solar energy available. One thing that seems to be a problem there is efficiency because the higher you compress any gas the more energy you need for the process and the more heat you produce (just think of an air pump you use to fill your bicycle getting hot if you pump quick enough). That heat needs to be removed at least partially and this process also has an environmental aspect. 
But take all that with a grain of salt - I am no expert in this field and base on that is my recollection of articles and information I read or watched.
